          "body": "Verse 15 is brief but structurally important: 'Then Solomon awoke, and behold, it was a dream.' The 'behold, it was a dream' is not a deflation but a recognition — the encounter was genuine, received through the medium of dream (a recognized mode of Old Testament theophany), and now Solomon knows what has happened. His immediate response is to travel to Jerusalem and stand before the ark of the covenant. This geographic and liturgical movement — from Gibeon's high place to Jerusalem's ark — is a theologizing of his itinerary. He goes to the legitimate center of Yahweh's covenantal presence. He offers burnt offerings (consecration) and peace offerings (communion and thanksgiving) and makes a feast for all his servants. The movement from dream to ark models the right response to divine gift: worship, specifically at the place where God has chosen to dwell. The ark is where the covenant was kept; standing before it after receiving a covenant promise is the exact right response. Peter Davids' observation about James 1:17 — that every good gift comes from above — finds its narrative counterpart here: Solomon immediately attributes the gift to its source and responds with worship."
