        "excerpt": "Now Solomon loved the LORD, walking in the statutes of his father David, except he sacrificed and burned incense on the high places.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with two data points that frame everything that follows. First, Solomon makes a marriage alliance with Pharaoh king of Egypt — taking Pharaoh's daughter as a wife (3:1). The narrator records it without immediate censure but not without implication. Deuteronomy 17:17 warns Israel's future king not to 'multiply wives for himself' lest his heart turn away; Deuteronomy 7:3-4 prohibits intermarriage with foreign nations precisely because 'they will turn your sons away from following Me.' The Egyptian marriage will eventually be explicitly flagged as problematic (1 Kings 11:1-2), but here it is placed at the chapter's opening as a quiet signal — the man who will receive unparalleled wisdom is already making compromises that will ultimately undo him.\n\nSecond, verse 3 delivers the narrator's summary verdict: Solomon loved the LORD and walked in David's statutes, 'except he sacrificed and burned incense on the high places.' The high-place worship is partially excused in verse 2 ('because there was no house built for the name of the LORD'), but the excuse applies to the people, not to Solomon specifically. The book of Kings will consistently use high-place worship as a theological index for evaluating kings (cf. 1 Kings 15:14; 22:43; 2 Kings 12:3; 14:4). For Solomon the verdict is mixed: genuine covenant love, genuine Davidic obedience, genuine incompleteness.\n\nThe pastoral significance of this portrait is often underestimated. God does not wait for Solomon to resolve his theological inconsistencies before appearing to him. He meets the mixed man at the great high place and offers him the chapter's generosity. This is not an endorsement of the mixture; the conditional of 3:14 and the eventual collapse of 1 Kings 11 make clear that the mixture has consequences. But it is a demonstration that God's elective purposes are not derailed by human incompleteness — they work through it, around it, and sometimes despite it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Raq* (except, 3:3) is a limiting particle that restricts what precedes it; it is the same particle used in Joshua 1:7 ('only be strong') and Deuteronomy 10:15 ('only the LORD had a delight in your fathers'). Its placement after the positive summary of Solomon's love creates what the Hebrew narrative tradition calls a 'shadow-clause' — a qualification that the narrator plants for later development. *Bamah* (high place) appears four times in 3:2-4 — the narrator's insistence on the word signals its theological weight."
