        "number": 3,
        "title": "The gift, the bonus, and the condition — God's response in 3:10-15",
        "range": "3:10-15",
        "excerpt": "Behold, I have given you a wise and discerning heart, so that there has been no one like you before you, nor shall one like you arise after you.",
        "body": "God's response has three movements: evaluation of the prayer (3:10-11), the superlative gift of wisdom (3:12), and the two additions — what was not asked (3:13) and what is conditionally promised (3:14).\n\nThe evaluation is striking in its emotional register: 'It was pleasing in the sight of the Lord' (3:10). The Hebrew *yatav* means to be good, to be well-pleasing. God is not reluctantly granting a clever request; He is delighted by it. The reason God names explicitly in 3:11 is not merely what Solomon asked for, but what he did not ask for — riches, long life, the death of his enemies. These three omissions are as theologically loaded as the one thing he requested. They represent the three temptations that corrupt every human authority: the desire to extend one's own comfort beyond its natural span (long life), the desire to accumulate wealth without reference to others' needs (riches), and the desire to eliminate those who threaten one's power (enemies). Solomon's prayer reveals a heart that has not yet succumbed to any of these — a remarkably pure political motive at this stage of his reign.\n\nThe gift itself is stated in superlatives that the narrator never uses again: 'there has been no one like you before you, nor shall one like you arise after you' (3:12). This is the narrator's voice endorsing God's speech. The New Testament picks up this very language — 'nor shall one like you arise after you' — and applies it in a negative register to the tribulation (Matthew 24:21), but here it is entirely positive: Solomon's wisdom is the historical apex of human wisdom given by divine endowment. The books of Proverbs and Ecclesiastes, both associated with Solomon, are the literary deposit of this gift.\n\nThe addition of riches and honor (3:13) embodies the principle Jesus articulates in Matthew 6:33 — 'seek first His kingdom and His righteousness, and all these things will be added to you.' Solomon sought the kingdom's tools (wisdom for justice) and received the kingdom's benefits (wealth and honor) without asking. Calvin comments that God is never a debtor to those who seek Him rightly; He always gives more than is requested.\n\nBut verse 14 is the chapter's conditional shadow: 'If you walk in My ways, keeping My statutes and commandments, as your father David walked, then I will prolong your days.' Long life is the one thing from Solomon's possible requests that God does not grant unconditionally; it is placed under covenant condition. The structure is deliberate. Wisdom, riches, and honor are God's prevenient gifts — they precede obedience and do not depend on it. Long life depends on the quality of the walk. The reader of 1 Kings already knows that 1 Kings 11 is coming; the 'if' of verse 14 is read against that backdrop with considerable pathos.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chakham* (wise, 3:12) and *nabun* (discerning, 3:12) appear together throughout Proverbs and represent the combination of practical intelligence and penetrating moral insight. *Derekh* (way, 3:14) is the full life-path, not an isolated act — the same word used when David is said to have 'walked in My ways.' *Arakh* (prolong, 3:14) is literally to lengthen — used of life, of days, of the tent-cords in Isaiah 54:2. The conditional form of 3:14 is the standard covenant-blessing formula of Deuteronomy (cf. Deuteronomy 28:1-2)."
