        "number": 4,
        "title": "Wisdom proven in the darkest domestic case — 3:16-28",
        "range": "3:16-28",
        "excerpt": "When all Israel heard of the judgment which the king had handed down, they feared the king, for they saw that the wisdom of God was in him to administer justice.",
        "body": "The transition from 3:15 to 3:16 is one of the most purposeful narrative juxtapositions in the Hebrew Bible. Solomon has just returned from the ark of the covenant, having worshipped in response to a divine theophany, having been told he is the wisest man in history — and the very next scene presents two unnamed prostitutes in a domestic dispute over a dead baby. The narrator is making a theological point about the nature of the wisdom God gives: it is not for the throne room and the diplomatic reception; it is for the most powerless people who stand before the bench.\n\nThe case is constructed to defeat normal judicial methods. No witnesses, no physical evidence distinguishable by any examination, two claimants of equal social standing (both prostitutes, both unnamed, both with newborns), and two claims that are perfectly symmetrical (3:22-23). The narrator reproduces the chiastic exchange of the women's claims in 3:22-23 with almost comic precision — every claim is immediately counterclaimed. Solomon summarizes the deadlock in verse 23, demonstrating that he has heard exactly what has been said and that the normal instruments of justice cannot cut through it.\n\nThe sword-command (3:24-25) is the wisdom breakthrough. It does not solve the evidential problem; it bypasses it entirely. Solomon creates a situation in which the two women must reveal not what they know but what they want. A woman who truly loves her child cannot consent to his death, even if it means surrendering the case. A woman who has already lost her child and has been driven by grief into self-serving deception has no such constraint. Verse 26 reports the true mother's response with the strongest available Hebrew vocabulary for maternal instinct: *nikhmeru rachamaeyha* — 'her compassionate bowels were stirred,' using the plural of *racham*, the word cognate with the word for 'womb.' The second woman's 'divide him!' reveals that she was willing to destroy the child rather than see him given to her rival.\n\nSolomon's verdict (3:27) is four Hebrew words: 'Give the living child to the first woman, and by no means kill him. She is his mother.' The brevity is part of the wisdom — the king does not explain his reasoning because the reasoning is self-evident to anyone who witnessed it. The verdict serves simultaneously as judgment in the case and as testimony about the judge. Verse 28 reports the national reverberations: all Israel heard, they feared the king, and they saw 'the wisdom of God was in him to administer justice (*mishpat*).' The word *mishpat* appears in both the petition (3:11) and the verdict (3:28), closing the chapter's theological arc. Solomon asked for discernment to administer *mishpat*; 3:28 confirms that is exactly what God gave and exactly what Solomon exercised.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Racham* (compassion, 3:26) is derived from *rechem* (womb); its plural *rachamim* is the standard Old Testament word for God's tender mercy and maternal compassion (Psalm 103:13; Isaiah 49:15). The use of *racham* here subtly aligns the true mother's love with the kind of love God has for Israel. *Mishpat* (justice, 3:28) is the word Solomon requested in 3:11 (translated 'justice' in NASB) — the narrator's closing use of the word confirms that the petition has been answered in the first case that came before the king."
